# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-waf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:aws-waf/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In computing, a **denial-of-service attack** (**DoS attack** /dɒs/ *doss*) is a cyberattack in which the perpetrator seeks to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users by temporarily or indefinitely disrupting services of a host connected to a network.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Denial of service is typically accomplished by flooding the targeted machine or resource with superfluous requests in an attempt to overload systems and prevent some or all legitimate requests from being fulfilled.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The range of attacks varies widely, spanning from inundating a server with millions of requests to slow its performance, overwhelming a server with a substantial amount of invalid data, to submitting requests with an illegitimate IP address.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In a **distributed denial-of-service attack** (**DDoS attack** /ˈdiː.dɒs/ *DEE-doss*), the incoming traffic flooding the victim originates from many different sources.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated strategies are required to mitigate this type of attack; simply attempting to block a single source is insufficient.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack is analogous to a group of people crowding the entry door of a shop, making it hard for legitimate customers to enter, thus disrupting trade and losing the business money.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Criminal perpetrators of DDoS attacks often target sites or services hosted on high-profile web servers such as banks or credit card payment gateways.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Revenge and blackmail, as well as hacktivism, can motivate these attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Panix, the third-oldest Internet service provider (ISP) in the world, was the target of what is thought to be the first DoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] On September 6, 1996, Panix was subject to a SYN flood attack, which brought down its services for several days while hardware vendors, notably Cisco, figured out a proper defense.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The release of sample code during the event led to the online attack of Sprint, EarthLink, E-Trade, and other major corporations in the year to follow.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2020, Amazon Web Services experienced an attack with a peak volume of 2.3 Tb/s.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In July 2021, Cloudflare boasted of protecting its client from a DDoS attack from a global Mirai botnet that was up to 17.2 million requests per second.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Russian DDoS prevention provider Yandex said it blocked an HTTP pipelining DDoS attack on Sept.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] 2021 that originated from unpatched Mikrotik networking gear.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In the first half of 2022, the Russian invasion of Ukraine significantly shaped the cyberthreat landscape, with an increase in cyberattacks attributed to both state-sponsored actors and global hacktivist activities.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The most notable event was a DDoS attack in February, the largest Ukraine has encountered, disrupting government and financial sector services.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This wave of cyber aggression extended to Western allies like the UK, the US, and Germany.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Particularly, the UK's financial sector saw an increase in DDoS attacks from nation-state actors and hacktivists, aimed at undermining Ukraine's allies.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2023, Cloudflare faced a 71 million requests per second attack which they claimed was the largest HTTP DDoS attack at the time.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP DDoS attacks are measured by HTTP requests per second instead of packets per second or bits per second.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] On July 10, 2023, the fanfiction platform Archive of Our Own (AO3) faced DDoS attacks, disrupting services.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Anonymous Sudan, claiming the attack for religious and political reasons, was viewed skeptically by AO3 and experts.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Flashpoint, a threat intelligence vendor, noted the group's past activities but doubted their stated motives.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] AO3, supported by the non-profit Organization for Transformative Works (OTW) and reliant on donations, is unlikely to meet the $30,000 Bitcoin ransom.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2023, the group of hacktivists NoName057 targeted several Italian financial institutions, through the execution of slow DoS attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] On 14 January 2024, they executed a DDoS attack on Swiss federal websites, prompted by President Zelensky's attendance at the Davos World Economic Forum.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Switzerland's National Cyber Security Centre quickly mitigated the attack, ensuring core federal services remained secure, despite temporary accessibility issues on some websites.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2023, exploitation of a new vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol resulted in the record for largest HTTP DDoS attack being broken twice, once with a 201 million requests per second attack observed by Cloudflare, and again with a 398 million requests per second attack observed by Google.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2024, Global Secure Layer observed and reported on a record-breaking packet DDoS at 3.15 billion packets per second, which targeted an undisclosed number of unofficial Minecraft game servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2024, the Internet Archive faced two severe DDoS attacks that brought the site completely offline, immediately following a previous attack that leaked records of over 31 million of the site's users.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The hacktivist group SN_Blackmeta claimed the DDoS attack as retribution for American involvement in the Gaza war, despite the Internet Archive being unaffiliated with the United States government; however, their link with the preceding data leak remains unclear.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare claims to have recorded and successfully autonomously blocked a 40-second DDoS attack on 23 September 2025, that reached a peak volume of 22.2 Tbit/s, which would be the largest DDoS attack to date.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare has stated that over 404,000 source IPs were used to target one IP address, and that the source IPs were not spoofed.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] According to Cloudflare, this came after several other large-scale DDoS attacks, each consecutively beating the previous record, including a 7.3 Tbit/s attack in May 2025 and an 11.5 Tbit/s attack on 1 September 2025.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Denial-of-service attacks are characterized by an explicit attempt by attackers to prevent legitimate use of a service.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] There are two general forms of DoS attacks: those that crash services and those that flood services.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The most serious attacks are distributed.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurs when multiple systems flood the bandwidth or resources of a targeted system, usually one or more web servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack uses more than one unique IP address or machines, often from thousands of hosts infected with malware.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial of service attack typically involves more than around 3–5 nodes on different networks; fewer nodes may qualify as a DoS attack but is not a DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Most of the time, attackers operate from an endpoint that is not their intended target, for example using another user's machine to attack a server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] By using another unsuspecting endpoint if it becomes compromised they can then move onto another workstation within the enterprise network.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] However, even faking lots of users and executing a DoS attack, a single attacker with few computers is still very limited in the amount of traffic they can generate.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacks are from multiple sources, it can be difficult for the host to identify and stop them.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The scale of DDoS attacks has continued to rise over recent years, by 2016 exceeding a terabit per second.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Some common examples of DDoS attacks are UDP flooding, SYN flooding and DNS amplification.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A **yo-yo attack** is a specific type of DoS/DDoS aimed at cloud-hosted applications which use autoscaling.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] During the attack, an attacker repeatedly changes between sending a lot of traffic (which causes a scale-up) and stopping the burst (causing a scale-down as a result).
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An **application layer DDoS attack** (sometimes referred to as **layer 7 DDoS attack**) is a form of DDoS attack where attackers target application-layer processes.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attack over-exercises specific functions or features of a website with the intention to disable those functions or features.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This application-layer attack is different from an entire network attack, and is often used against financial institutions to distract IT and security personnel from security breaches.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2013, application-layer DDoS attacks represented 20% of all DDoS attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] According to research by Akamai Technologies, there have been "51 percent more application layer attacks" from Q4 2013 to Q4 2014 and "16 percent more" from Q3 2014 to Q4 2014.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In November 2017; Junade Ali, an engineer at Cloudflare noted that whilst network-level attacks continue to be of high capacity, they were occurring less frequently.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Ali further noted that although network-level attacks were becoming less frequent, data from Cloudflare demonstrated that application-layer attacks were still showing no sign of slowing down.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The simplest DoS attack relies primarily on brute force, flooding the target with an overwhelming flux of packets, oversaturating its connection bandwidth or depleting the target's system resources.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Bandwidth-saturating floods rely on the attacker's ability to generate the overwhelming flux of packets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A common way of achieving this today is via distributed denial-of-service, employing a botnet.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An application layer DDoS attack is done mainly for specific targeted purposes, including disrupting transactions and access to databases.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It requires fewer resources than network layer attacks but often accompanies them.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An attack may be disguised to look like legitimate traffic, except it targets specific application packets or functions.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attack on the application layer can disrupt services such as the retrieval of information or search functions on a website.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An **advanced persistent DoS** (APDoS) is associated with an advanced persistent threat and requires specialized DDoS mitigation.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can persist for weeks; the longest continuous period noted so far lasted 38 days.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This attack involved approximately 50+ petabits (50,000+ terabits) of malicious traffic.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers in this scenario may tactically switch between several targets to create a diversion to evade defensive DDoS countermeasures but all the while eventually concentrating the main thrust of the attack onto a single victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In this scenario, attackers with continuous access to several very powerful network resources are capable of sustaining a prolonged campaign generating enormous levels of unamplified DDoS traffic.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Some vendors provide so-called *booter* or *stresser* services, which have simple web-based front ends, and accept payment over the web.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Marketed and promoted as stress-testing tools, they can be used to perform unauthorized denial-of-service attacks, and allow technically unsophisticated attackers access to sophisticated attack tools.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Usually powered by a botnet, the traffic produced by a consumer stresser can range anywhere from 5-50 Gbit/s, which can, in most cases, deny the average home user internet access.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A Markov-modulated denial-of-service attack occurs when the attacker disrupts control packets using a hidden Markov model.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A setting in which Markov-model-based attacks are prevalent is online gaming as the disruption of the control packet undermines gameplay and system functionality.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In cases such as MyDoom and Slowloris, the tools are embedded in malware and launch their attacks without the knowledge of the system owner.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Stacheldraht is a classic example of a DDoS tool.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker using automated routines to exploit vulnerabilities in programs that accept remote connections running on the targeted remote hosts.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Each handler can control up to a thousand agents.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In other cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The Low Orbit Ion Cannon has typically been used in this way.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Along with High Orbit Ion Cannon a wide variety of DDoS tools are available today, including paid and free versions, with different features available.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] There is an underground market for these in hacker-related forums and IRC channels.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Application-layer attacks employ DoS-causing exploits and can cause server-running software to fill the disk space or consume all available memory or CPU time.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks may use specific packet types or connection requests to saturate finite resources by, for example, occupying the maximum number of open connections or filling the victim's disk space with logs.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An attacker with shell-level access to a victim's computer may slow it until it is unusable or crash it by using a fork bomb.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Another kind of application-level DoS attack is XDoS (or XML DoS) which can be controlled by modern web application firewalls (WAFs).
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] All attacks belonging to the category of *timeout exploiting*.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Slow DoS attacks implement an application-layer attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Examples of threats are Slowloris, establishing pending connections with the victim, or SlowDroid, an attack running on mobile devices.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Another target of DDoS attacks may be to produce added costs for the application operator, when the latter uses resources based on cloud computing.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In this case, normally application-used resources are tied to a needed quality of service (QoS) level (e.g. responses should be less than 200 ms) and this rule is usually linked to automated software (e.g.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Amazon CloudWatch) to raise more virtual resources from the provider to meet the defined QoS levels for the increased requests.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The main incentive behind such attacks may be to drive the application owner to raise the elasticity levels to handle the increased application traffic, to cause financial losses, or force them to become less competitive.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A *banana attack* is another particular type of DoS.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It involves redirecting outgoing messages from the client back onto the client, preventing outside access, as well as flooding the client with the sent packets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Pulsing zombies are compromised computers that are directed to launch intermittent and short-lived flooding of victim websites with the intent of merely slowing it rather than crashing it.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This type of attack, referred to as *degradation-of-service*, can be more difficult to detect and can disrupt and hamper connection to websites for prolonged periods of time, potentially causing more overall disruption than a denial-of-service attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Exposure of degradation-of-service attacks is complicated further by the matter of discerning whether the server is really being attacked or is experiencing higher than normal legitimate traffic loads.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If an attacker mounts an attack from a single host, it would be classified as a DoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Any attack against availability would be classed as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] On the other hand, if an attacker uses many systems to simultaneously launch attacks against a remote host, this would be classified as a DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Malware can carry DDoS attack mechanisms; one of the better-known examples of this was MyDoom.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Its DoS mechanism was triggered on a specific date and time.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This type of DDoS involved hardcoding the target IP address before releasing the malware and no further interaction was necessary to launch the attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A system may also be compromised with a trojan containing a zombie agent.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers can also break into systems using automated tools that exploit flaws in programs that listen for connections from remote hosts.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This scenario primarily concerns systems acting as servers on the web.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers, which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents, which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In some cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback, organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can use different types of internet packets such as TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These collections of compromised systems are known as botnets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS tools like Stacheldraht still use classic DoS attack methods centered on IP spoofing and amplification like smurf attacks and fraggle attacks (types of bandwidth consumption attacks).
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] SYN floods (a resource starvation attack) may also be used.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Newer tools can use DNS servers for DoS purposes.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike MyDoom's DDoS mechanism, botnets can be turned against any IP address.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Script kiddies use them to deny the availability of well known websites to legitimate users.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated attackers use DDoS tools for the purposes of extortion – including against their business rivals.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It has been reported that there are new attacks from internet of things (IoT) devices that have been involved in denial of service attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] One such attack peaked at around 20,000 requests per second; it came from around 900 CCTV cameras.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] UK's GCHQ has tools built for DDoS, named PREDATORS FACE and ROLLING THUNDER.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Simple attacks such as SYN floods may appear with a wide range of source IP addresses, giving the appearance of a distributed DoS.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These flood attacks do not require completion of the TCP three-way handshake and attempt to exhaust the destination SYN queue or the server bandwidth.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Because the source IP addresses can be trivially spoofed, an attack could come from a limited set of sources, or may even originate from a single host.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Stack enhancements such as SYN cookies may be effective mitigation against SYN queue flooding but do not address bandwidth exhaustion.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2022, TCP attacks were the leading method in DDoS incidents, accounting for 63% of all DDoS activity.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This includes tactics like TCP SYN, TCP ACK, and TCP floods.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] With TCP being the most widespread networking protocol, its attacks are expected to remain prevalent in the DDoS threat scene.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2015, DDoS botnets such as DD4BC grew in prominence, taking aim at financial institutions.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Cyber-extortionists typically begin with a low-level attack and a warning that a larger attack will be carried out if a ransom is not paid in bitcoin.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Security experts recommend targeted websites to not pay the ransom.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attackers tend to get into an extended extortion scheme once they recognize that the target is ready to pay.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] First discovered in 2009, the HTTP slow POST attack sends a complete, legitimate HTTP POST header, which includes a *Content-Length* field to specify the size of the message body to follow.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] However, the attacker then proceeds to send the actual message body at an extremely slow rate (e.g.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Due to the entire message being correct and complete, the target server will attempt to obey the *Content-Length* field in the header and wait for the entire body of the message to be transmitted, which can take a very long time.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker establishes hundreds or even thousands of such connections until all resources for incoming connections on the victim server are exhausted, making any further connections impossible until all data has been sent.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It is notable that unlike many other DoS or DDoS attacks, which try to subdue the server by overloading its network or CPU, an HTTP slow POST attack targets the *logical* resources of the victim, which means the victim would still have enough network bandwidth and processing power to operate.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Combined with the fact that the Apache HTTP Server will, by default, accept requests up to 2GB in size, this attack can be particularly powerful.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP slow POST attacks are difficult to differentiate from legitimate connections and are therefore able to bypass some protection systems.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] OWASP, an open source web application security project, released a tool to test the security of servers against this type of attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A Challenge Collapsar (CC) attack is an attack where standard HTTP requests are sent to a targeted web server frequently.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) in the requests require complicated time-consuming algorithms or database operations which may exhaust the resources of the targeted web server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2004, a Chinese hacker nicknamed KiKi invented a hacking tool to send these kinds of requests to attack a NSFOCUS firewall named Collapsar, and thus the hacking tool was known as Challenge Collapsar, or *CC* for short.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Consequently, this type of attack got the name *CC attack*.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A smurf attack relies on misconfigured network devices that allow packets to be sent to all computer hosts on a particular network via the broadcast address of the network, rather than a specific machine.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker will send large numbers of IP packets with the source address faked to appear to be the address of the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Most devices on a network will, by default, respond to this by sending a reply to the source IP address.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If the number of machines on the network that receive and respond to these packets is very large, the victim's computer will be flooded with traffic.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This overloads the victim's computer and can even make it unusable during such an attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Ping flood is based on sending the victim an overwhelming number of ping packets, usually using the *ping* command from Unix-like hosts.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It is very simple to launch, the primary requirement being access to greater bandwidth than the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Ping of death is based on sending the victim a malformed ping packet, which will lead to a system crash on a vulnerable system.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The BlackNurse attack is an example of an attack taking advantage of the required Destination Port Unreachable ICMP packets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A specific example of a nuke attack that gained some prominence is the WinNuke, which exploited the vulnerability in the NetBIOS handler in Windows 95.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A string of out-of-band data was sent to TCP port 139 of the victim's machine, causing it to lock up and display a Blue Screen of Death.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers have found a way to exploit a number of bugs in peer-to-peer servers to initiate DDoS attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The most aggressive of these peer-to-peer-DDoS attacks exploits the DC++ file sharing network.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] With peer-to-peer attacks there is no botnet and the attacker does not have to communicate with the clients it subverts.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Instead, the attacker acts as a *puppet master*, instructing clients of large peer-to-peer file sharing hubs to disconnect from their peer-to-peer network and to connect to the victim's website instead.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Permanent denial-of-service (PDoS), also known loosely as phlashing, is an attack that damages a system so badly that it requires replacement or reinstallation of hardware.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike the distributed denial-of-service attack, a PDoS attack exploits security flaws which allow remote administration on the management interfaces of the victim's hardware, such as routers, printers, or other networking hardware.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The PDoS is a pure hardware-targeted attack that can be much faster and requires fewer resources than using a botnet in a DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Because of these features, and the potential and high probability of security exploits on network-enabled embedded devices, this technique has come to the attention of numerous hacking communities.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] BrickerBot, a piece of malware that targeted IoT devices, used PDoS attacks to disable its targets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] PhlashDance is a tool created by Rich Smith (an employee of Hewlett-Packard's Systems Security Lab) used to detect and demonstrate PDoS vulnerabilities at the 2008 EUSecWest Applied Security Conference in London, UK.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service attack may involve sending forged requests of some type to a very large number of computers that will reply to the requests.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Using Internet Protocol address spoofing, the source address is set to that of the targeted victim, which means all the replies will go to (and flood) the target.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This reflected attack form is sometimes called a distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS) attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] ICMP echo request attacks (Smurf attacks) can be considered one form of reflected attack, as the flooding hosts send Echo Requests to the broadcast addresses of mis-configured networks, thereby enticing hosts to send Echo Reply packets to the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Some early DDoS programs implemented a distributed form of this attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Amplification attacks are used to magnify the bandwidth that is sent to a victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Many services can be exploited to act as reflectors, some harder to block than others.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] DNS amplification attacks involves an attacker sending a DNS name lookup request to one or more public DNS servers, spoofing the source IP address of the targeted victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker tries to request as much information as possible, thus amplifying the DNS response that is sent to the targeted victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Since the size of the request is significantly smaller than the response, the attacker is easily able to increase the amount of traffic directed at the target.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) and Network Time Protocol (NTP) can also be exploited as reflectors in an amplification attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An example of an amplified DDoS attack through the NTP is through a command called monlist, which sends the details of the last 600 hosts that have requested the time from the NTP server back to the requester.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A small request to this time server can be sent using a spoofed source IP address of some victim, which results in a response 556.9 times the size of the request being sent to the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This becomes amplified when using botnets that all send requests with the same spoofed IP source, which will result in a massive amount of data being sent back to the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It is very difficult to defend against these types of attacks because the response data is coming from legitimate servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These attack requests are also sent through UDP, which does not require a connection to the server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This means that the source IP is not verified when a request is received by the server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] To bring awareness of these vulnerabilities, campaigns have been started that are dedicated to finding amplification vectors which have led to people fixing their resolvers or having the resolvers shut down completely.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The Mirai botnet works by using a computer worm to infect hundreds of thousands of IoT devices across the internet.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The worm propagates through networks and systems taking control of poorly protected IoT devices such as thermostats, Wi-Fi-enabled clocks, and washing machines.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The owner or user will usually have no immediate indication of when the device becomes infected.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The IoT device itself is not the direct target of the attack; it is used as part of a larger attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Once the hacker has enslaved the desired number of devices, they instruct the devices to try to contact an ISP.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2016, a Mirai botnet attacked Dyn which is the ISP for sites such as Twitter, Netflix, etc.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] As soon as this occurred, these websites were all unreachable for several hours.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] RUDY attack targets web applications by starvation of available sessions on the web server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Much like Slowloris, RUDY keeps sessions at a halt using never-ending POST transmissions and sending an arbitrarily large content-length header value.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Manipulating maximum segment size and selective acknowledgement (SACK) may be used by a remote peer to cause a denial of service by an integer overflow in the Linux kernel, potentially causing a kernel panic.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The shrew attack is a denial-of-service attack on the Transmission Control Protocol where the attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It exploits a weakness in TCP's re-transmission timeout mechanism, using short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on the same link.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A slow read attack sends legitimate application layer requests, but reads responses very slowly, keeping connections open longer hoping to exhaust the server's connection pool.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The slow read is achieved by advertising a very small number for the TCP Receive Window size, and at the same time emptying clients' TCP receive buffer slowly, which causes a very low data flow rate.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A sophisticated low-bandwidth DDoS attack is a form of DoS that uses less traffic and increases its effectiveness by aiming at a weak point in the victim's system design, i.e., the attacker sends traffic consisting of complicated requests to the system.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Essentially, a sophisticated DDoS attack is lower in cost due to its use of less traffic, is smaller in size making it more difficult to identify, and it can hurt systems which are protected by flow control mechanisms.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A SYN flood occurs when a host sends a flood of TCP/SYN packets, often with a forged sender address.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Each of these packets is handled like a connection request, causing the server to spawn a half-open connection, send back a TCP/SYN-ACK packet, and wait for a packet in response from the sender address.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] However, because the sender's address is forged, the response never comes.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These half-open connections exhaust the available connections the server can make, keeping it from responding to legitimate requests until after the attack ends.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A **teardrop attack** involves sending mangled IP fragments with overlapping, oversized payloads to the target machine.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This can crash various operating systems because of a bug in their TCP/IP fragmentation re-assembly code.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Windows 3.1x, Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, as well as versions of Linux before versions 2.0.32 and 2.1.63 are vulnerable to this attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] One of the fields in an IP header is the *fragment offset* field, indicating the starting position, or offset, of the data contained in a fragmented packet relative to the data in the original packet.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If the sum of the offset and size of one fragmented packet differs from that of the next fragmented packet, the packets overlap.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] When this happens, a server vulnerable to teardrop attacks is unable to reassemble the packets resulting in a denial-of-service condition.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Voice over IP has made abusive origination of large numbers of telephone voice calls inexpensive and easily automated while permitting call origins to be misrepresented through caller ID spoofing.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS can exist even without Internet telephony.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In the 2002 New Hampshire Senate election phone jamming scandal, telemarketers were used to flood political opponents with spurious calls to jam phone banks on election day.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Widespread publication of a number can also flood it with enough calls to render it unusable, as happened by accident in 1981 with multiple +1-area code-867-5309 subscribers inundated by hundreds of calls daily in response to the song "867-5309/Jenny".
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS differs from other telephone harassment (such as prank calls and obscene phone calls) by the number of calls originated.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] By occupying lines continuously with repeated automated calls, the victim is prevented from making or receiving both routine and emergency telephone calls.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Related exploits include SMS flooding attacks and black fax or continuous fax transmission by using a loop of paper at the sender.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It takes more router resources to drop a packet with a TTL value of 1 or less than it does to forward a packet with a higher TTL value.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] When a packet is dropped due to TTL expiry, the router CPU must generate and send an ICMP time exceeded response.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Generating many of these responses can overload the router's CPU.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A UPnP attack uses an existing vulnerability in Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol to get past network security and flood a target's network and servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The attack is based on a DNS amplification technique, but the attack mechanism is a UPnP router that forwards requests from one outer source to another.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The UPnP router returns the data on an unexpected UDP port from a bogus IP address, making it harder to take simple action to shut down the traffic flood.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] According to the Imperva researchers, the most effective way to stop this attack is for companies to lock down UPnP routers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2014, it was discovered that Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) was being used in DDoS attacks known as an SSDP reflection attac*k* *with amplification*.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Many devices, including some residential routers, have a vulnerability in the UPnP software that allows an attacker to get replies from UDP port 1900 to a destination address of their choice.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] With a botnet of thousands of devices, the attackers can generate sufficient packet rates and occupy bandwidth to saturate links, causing the denial of service.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Because of this weakness, the network company Cloudflare has described SSDP as the "Stupidly Simple DDoS Protocol".
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Defensive responses to denial-of-service attacks typically involve the use of a combination of attack detection, traffic classification and response tools, aiming to block traffic the tools identify as illegitimate and allow traffic that they identify as legitimate.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A list of response tools include the following.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] All traffic destined to the victim is diverted to pass through a *cleaning center* or a *scrubbing center* via various methods such as: changing the victim IP address in the DNS system, tunneling methods (GRE/VRF, MPLS, SDN), proxies, digital cross connects, or even direct circuits.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The cleaning center separates *bad* traffic (DDoS and also other common internet attacks) and only passes good legitimate traffic to the victim server.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The victim needs central connectivity to the Internet to use this kind of service unless they happen to be located within the same facility as the cleaning center.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS attacks can overwhelm any type of hardware firewall, and passing malicious traffic through large and mature networks becomes more and more effective and economically sustainable against DDoS.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware is intelligent hardware placed on the network before traffic reaches the servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It can be used on networks in conjunction with routers and switches and as part of bandwidth management.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware analyzes data packets as they enter the network, and identifies and drops dangerous or suspicious flows.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Approaches to detection of DDoS attacks against cloud-based applications may be based on an application layer analysis, indicating whether incoming bulk traffic is legitimate.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These approaches mainly rely on an identified path of value inside the application and monitor the progress of requests on this path, through markers called *key completion indicators*.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In essence, these techniques are statistical methods of assessing the behavior of incoming requests to detect if something unusual or abnormal is going on.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An analogy is to a brick-and-mortar department store where customers spend, on average, a known percentage of their time on different activities such as picking up items and examining them, putting them back, filling a basket, waiting to pay, paying, and leaving.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If a mob of customers arrived in the store and spent all their time picking up items and putting them back, but never made any purchases, this could be flagged as unusual behavior.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] With blackhole routing, all the traffic to the attacked DNS or IP address is sent to a *black hole* (null interface or a non-existent server).
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] To be more efficient and avoid affecting network connectivity, it can be managed by the ISP.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A DNS sinkhole routes traffic to a valid IP address which analyzes traffic and rejects bad packets.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Sinkholing may not be efficient for severe attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion prevention systems (IPS) are effective if the attacks have signatures associated with them.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] However, the trend among attacks is to have legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion-prevention systems that work on content recognition cannot block behavior-based DoS attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An ASIC based IPS may detect and block denial-of-service attacks because they have the processing power and the granularity to analyze the attacks and act like a circuit breaker in an automated way.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] More focused on the problem than IPS, a DoS defense system (DDS) can block connection-based DoS attacks and those with legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A DDS can also address both protocol attacks (such as teardrop and ping of death) and rate-based attacks (such as ICMP floods and SYN floods).
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] DDS has a purpose-built system that can easily identify and obstruct denial of service attacks at a greater speed than a software-based system.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In the case of a simple attack, a firewall can be adjusted to deny all incoming traffic from the attackers, based on protocols, ports, or the originating IP addresses.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] More complex attacks will however be hard to block with simple rules: for example, if there is an ongoing attack on port 80 (web service), it is not possible to drop all incoming traffic on this port because doing so will prevent the server from receiving and serving legitimate traffic.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Additionally, firewalls may be too deep in the network hierarchy, with routers being adversely affected before the traffic gets to the firewall.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Also, many security tools still do not support IPv6 or may not be configured properly, so the firewalls may be bypassed during the attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Similar to switches, routers have some rate-limiting and ACL capabilities.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Most routers can be easily overwhelmed under a DoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS using FP4 or FP5 processors offers DDoS protection.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS also uses big data analytics-based Nokia Deepfield Defender for DDoS protection.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Cisco IOS has optional features that can reduce the impact of flooding.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Most switches have some rate-limiting and ACL capability.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Some switches provide automatic or system-wide rate limiting, traffic shaping, delayed binding (TCP splicing), deep packet inspection and bogon filtering (bogus IP filtering) to detect and remediate DoS attacks through automatic rate filtering and WAN Link failover and balancing.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These schemes will work as long as the DoS attacks can be prevented by using them.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] For example, SYN flood can be prevented using delayed binding or TCP splicing.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Similarly, content-based DoS may be prevented using deep packet inspection.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks using Martian packets can be prevented using bogon filtering.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Automatic rate filtering can work as long as set rate thresholds have been set correctly.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] WAN-link failover will work as long as both links have a DoS prevention mechanism.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Threats may be associated with specific TCP or UDP port numbers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking these ports at the firewall can mitigate an attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] For example, in an SSDP reflection attack, the key mitigation is to block incoming UDP traffic on port 1900.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking specific Time to live (TTL) values based on the network path length can be a viable option for blocking spoofed attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service can occur when a system ends up denied, not due to a deliberate attack by a single individual or group of individuals, but simply due to a sudden enormous spike in popularity.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This can happen when an extremely popular website posts a prominent link to a second, less well-prepared site, for example, as part of a news story.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The result is that a significant proportion of the primary site's regular users – potentially hundreds of thousands of people – click that link in the space of a few hours, having the same effect on the target website as a DDoS attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] A VIPDoS is the same, but specifically when the link was posted by a celebrity.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] When Michael Jackson died in 2009, websites such as Google and Twitter slowed down or even crashed.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Many sites' servers thought the requests were from a virus or spyware trying to cause a denial-of-service attack, warning users that their queries looked like "automated requests from a computer virus or spyware application".
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] News sites and link sites – sites whose primary function is to provide links to interesting content elsewhere on the Internet – are most likely to cause this phenomenon.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The canonical example is the Slashdot effect when receiving traffic from Slashdot.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] It is also known as "the Reddit hug of death" and "the Digg effect".
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Similar unintentional denial-of-service can also occur via other media, e.g. when a URL is mentioned on television.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In March 2014, after Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 went missing, DigitalGlobe launched a crowdsourcing service on which users could help search for the missing jet in satellite images.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The response overwhelmed the company's servers.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service may also result from a prescheduled event created by the website itself, as was the case of the Census in Australia in 2016.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Legal action has been taken in at least one such case.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In 2006, Universal Tube & Rollform Equipment Corporation sued YouTube: massive numbers of would-be YouTube.com users accidentally typed the tube company's URL, utube.com.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] As a result, the tube company ended up having to spend large amounts of money on upgrading its bandwidth.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Routers have also been known to create unintentional DoS attacks, as both D-Link and Netgear routers have overloaded NTP servers by flooding them without respecting the restrictions of client types or geographical limitations.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In computer network security, backscatter is a side-effect of a spoofed denial-of-service attack.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In this kind of attack, the attacker spoofs the source address in IP packets sent to the victim.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In general, the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets, so the victim responds to the spoofed packets as it normally would.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] These response packets are known as backscatter.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacker is spoofing source addresses randomly, the backscatter response packets from the victim will be sent back to random destinations.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] This effect can be used by network telescopes as indirect evidence of such attacks.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The term *backscatter analysis* refers to observing backscatter packets arriving at a statistically significant portion of the IP address space to determine the characteristics of DoS attacks and victims.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Many jurisdictions have laws under which denial-of-service attacks are illegal.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] UNCTAD highlights that 156 countries, or 80% globally, have enacted cybercrime laws to combat its widespread impact.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Adoption rates vary by region, with Europe at a 91% rate, and Africa at 72%.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In the US, denial-of-service attacks may be considered a federal crime under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act with penalties that include years of imprisonment.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section of the US Department of Justice handles cases of DoS and DDoS.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In one example, in July 2019, Austin Thompson, aka DerpTrolling, was sentenced to 27 months in prison and $95,000 in restitution by a federal court for conducting multiple DDoS attacks on major video gaming companies, disrupting their systems for hours to days.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In European countries, committing criminal denial-of-service attacks may, as a minimum, lead to arrest.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] The United Kingdom is unusual in that it specifically outlawed denial-of-service attacks and set a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison with the Police and Justice Act 2006, which amended Section 3 of the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] In January 2019, Europol announced that "actions are currently underway worldwide to track down the users" of Webstresser.org, a former DDoS marketplace that was shut down in April 2018 as part of Operation PowerOFF.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] Europol said UK police were conducting a number of "live operations" targeting over 250 users of Webstresser and other DDoS services.
[src:aws-waf/denial-of-service-attack] On January 7, 2013, Anonymous posted a petition on the whitehouse.gov site asking that DDoS be recognized as a legal form of protest similar to the Occupy movement, the claim being that the similarity in the purpose of both is same.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] In computing, a **firewall** is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on configurable security rules.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] A firewall typically establishes a barrier between a trusted network and an untrusted network, such as the Internet or between several VLANs.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewalls can be categorized as network-based or host-based.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The term *firewall* originally referred to a wall to confine a fire within a line of adjacent buildings.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Later uses refer to similar structures, such as the metal sheet separating the engine compartment of a vehicle or aircraft from the passenger compartment.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The term was applied in the 1980s to network technology that emerged when the Internet was fairly new in terms of its global use and connectivity.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The predecessors to firewalls for network security were routers used in the 1980s.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Because they already segregated networks, routers could filter packets crossing them.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Before it was used in real-life computing, the term appeared in John Badham's 1983 computer‑hacking movie *WarGames*, spoken by the bearded and bespectacled programmer named Paul Richter, which possibly inspired its later use.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] One of the earliest commercially successful firewall and network address translation (NAT) products was the PIX (Private Internet eXchange) Firewall, invented in 1994 by Network Translation Inc., a startup founded and run by John Mayes.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The PIX Firewall technology was coded by Brantley Coile as a consultant software developer.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Recognizing the emerging IPv4 address depletion problem, they designed the PIX to enable organizations to securely connect private networks to the public internet using a limited number of registered IP addresses.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The innovative PIX solution quickly gained industry acclaim, earning the prestigious "Hot Product of the Year" award from Data Communications Magazine in January 1995.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Cisco Systems, seeking to expand into the rapidly growing network security market, subsequently acquired Network Translation Inc. in November 1995 to obtain the rights to the PIX technology.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The PIX became one of Cisco's flagship firewall product lines before eventually being succeeded by the Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA) platform introduced in 2005.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewalls are categorized as a network-based or a host-based system.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Network-based firewalls are positioned between two or more networks, typically between the local area network (LAN) and wide area network (WAN), their basic function being to control the flow of data between connected networks.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] They are either a software appliance running on general-purpose hardware, a hardware appliance running on special-purpose hardware, or a virtual appliance running on a virtual host controlled by a hypervisor.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewall appliances may also offer non-firewall functionality, such as DHCP or VPN services.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Host-based firewalls are deployed directly on the host itself to control network traffic or other computing resources.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] This can be a daemon or service as a part of the operating system or an agent application for protection.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The first reported type of network firewall is called a packet filter which inspects packets transferred between computers.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The firewall maintains an access-control list which dictates what packets will be looked at and what action should be applied, if any, with the default action set to silent discard.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Three basic actions regarding the packet consist of a silent discard, discard with Internet Control Message Protocol or TCP reset response to the sender, and forward to the next hop.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Packets may be filtered by source and destination IP addresses, protocol, or source and destination ports.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The first paper published on firewall technology was in 1987 when engineers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) developed filter systems known as packet filter firewalls.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] At AT&T Bell Labs, Bill Cheswick and Steve Bellovin continued their research in packet filtering and developed a working model for their own company based on their original first-generation architecture.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] In 1992, Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson released a paper on BSD Packet Filter (BPF) while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] From 1989 to 1990, three colleagues from AT&T Bell Laboratories, Dave Presotto, Janardan Sharma, and Kshitij Nigam, developed the second generation of firewalls, calling them circuit-level gateways.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard released an application firewall known as Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) in October 1993.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] This became the basis for Gauntlet firewall at Trusted Information Systems.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The key benefit of application layer filtering is that it can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port, or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] It can also provide unified security management including enforced encrypted DNS and virtual private networking.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Endpoint-based application firewalls function by determining whether a process should accept any given connection.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Application firewalls filter connections by examining the process ID of data packets against a rule set for the local process involved in the data transmission.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Application firewalls accomplish their function by hooking into socket calls to filter the connections between the application layer and the lower layers.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Application firewalls that hook into socket calls are also referred to as socket filters.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] At the core of a firewall's operation are the policies that govern its decision-making process.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] These policies, collectively known as firewall rules, are the specific guidelines that determine the traffic allowed or blocked across a network's boundaries.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewall rules are based on the evaluation of network packets against predetermined security criteria.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] A network packet, which carries data across networks, must match certain attributes defined in a rule to be allowed through the firewall.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Zones are logical segments within a network that group together devices with similar security requirements.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] By partitioning a network into zones, such as "Technical", "WAN", "LAN", "Public," "Private," "DMZ", and "Wireless," administrators can enforce policies that control the flow of traffic between them.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Each zone has its own level of trust and is governed by specific firewall rules that regulate the ingress and egress of data.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] A typical default is to allow all traffic from LAN to WAN, and to drop all traffic from WAN to LAN.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] In networking terms, services are specific functions typically identified by a network port and protocol.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Common examples include HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic) on ports 80 and 443, FTP (file transfer) on port 21, and SMTP (email) on port 25.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Services are the engines behind the applications users depend on.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] From a security aspect, controlling access to services is crucial because services are common targets for exploitation.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewalls employ rules that stipulate which services should be accessible, to whom, and in what context.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] For example, a firewall might be configured to block incoming FTP requests to prevent unauthorized file uploads but allow outgoing HTTPS requests for web browsing.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Applications refer to the software systems that users interact with while on the network.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] They can range from web browsers and email clients to complex database systems and cloud-based services.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] In network security, applications are important because different types of traffic can pose varying security risks.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Thus, firewall rules can be crafted to identify and control traffic based on the application generating or receiving it.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] By using application awareness, firewalls can allow, deny, or limit traffic for specific applications according to organizational policies and compliance requirements, thereby mitigating potential threats from vulnerable or undesired applications.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Application can both be a grouping of services, or a L7 inspection.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Implementing firewall rules based on IP addresses alone is often insufficient due to the dynamic nature of user location and device usage.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] User ID will be translated to an IP address.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] This is where the concept of "User ID" makes a significant impact.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] User ID allows firewall rules to be crafted based on individual user identities, rather than just fixed source or destination IP addresses.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] This enhances security by enabling more granular control over who can access certain network resources, regardless of where they are connecting from or what device they are using.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] The User ID technology is typically integrated into firewall systems through the use of directory services such as Active Directory, LDAP, RADIUS or TACACS+.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] These services link the user's login information to their network activities.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] By doing this, the firewall can apply rules and policies that correspond to user groups, roles, or individual user accounts instead of purely relying on the network topology.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Consider a school that wants to restrict access to a social media server from students.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] They can create a rule in the firewall that utilises User ID information to enforce this policy.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] User Identification — The firewall maps network traffic to specific user IDs by interpreting authentication logs.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] When a user logs on, the firewall associates that login with the user's IP address.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Define User Groups — Within the firewall's management interface, define user groups based on the directory service.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] For example, create groups such as "Students".
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] With this setup, only users who authenticate and are identified as members of "Students" are denied to access social media servers.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] All other traffic, starting from LAN interfaces, will be allowed.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Setting up a firewall is a complex and error-prone task.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] A network may face security issues due to configuration errors.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Firewall policies are typically configured according to the type of network in use, such as public or private environments.
[src:aws-waf/firewall-computing] Administrators define rules that permit or restrict traffic in order to reduce exposure to threats like unauthorized access, malware, or other forms of cyberattack.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Network security starts with authentication, commonly with a username and a password.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Since this requires just one detail authenticating the user name—i.e., the password—this is sometimes termed one-factor authentication.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] With two-factor authentication, something the user 'has' is also used (e.g., a security token or 'dongle', an ATM card, or a mobile phone); and with three-factor authentication, something the user 'is' is also used (e.g., a fingerprint or retinal scan).
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Once authenticated, a firewall enforces access policies such as what services are allowed to be accessed by the network users.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Though effective to prevent unauthorized access, this component may fail to check potentially harmful content such as computer worms or Trojans being transmitted over the network.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Anti-virus software or an intrusion prevention system (IPS) help detect and inhibit the action of such malware.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] An anomaly-based intrusion detection system may also monitor the network like wireshark traffic and may be logged for audit purposes and for later high-level analysis.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Newer systems combining unsupervised machine learning with full network traffic analysis can detect active network attackers from malicious insiders or targeted external attackers that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Communication between two hosts using a network may be encrypted to maintain security and privacy.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Honeypots, essentially decoy network-accessible resources, may be deployed in a network as surveillance and early-warning tools, as the honeypots are not normally accessed for legitimate purposes.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Honeypots are placed at a point in the network where they appear vulnerable and undefended, but they are actually isolated and monitored.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Techniques used by the attackers that attempt to compromise these decoy resources are studied during and after an attack to keep an eye on new exploitation techniques.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Such analysis may be used to further tighten security of the actual network being protected by the honeypot.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A honeypot can also direct an attacker's attention away from legitimate servers.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A honeypot encourages attackers to spend their time and energy on the decoy server while distracting their attention from the data on the real server.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Similar to a honeypot, a honeynet is a network set up with intentional vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Its purpose is also to invite attacks so that the attacker's methods can be studied and that information can be used to increase network security.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A honeynet typically contains one or more honeypots.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Previous research on network security was mostly about using tools to secure transactions and information flow, and how well users knew about and used these tools.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] However, more recently, the discussion has expanded to consider information security in the broader context of the digital economy and society.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] This is indicative of network security topics covering not just individual users and tools, but also conversations about the larger culture of information security in our digital world.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Security management for networks is different for all kinds of situations.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A home or small office may only require basic security while large businesses may require high-maintenance and advanced software and hardware to prevent malicious attacks from hacking and spamming.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] In order to minimize susceptibility to malicious attacks from external threats to the network, corporations often employ tools which carry out network security verifications.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] These tools can also mitigate and detect internal human behavior such as insider threats and email storms.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] The human element is often the weakest link in any network security system, as evidenced by a study in 2014 which found that employees often do not see themselves as part of their organization's information security effort and often take actions that impede organizational changes.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] The move from centralized systems to cloud-based and hybrid work environments has made it harder to monitor networks, especially with traditional tools.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A Broadcom survey found that 65% of respondents rely on third-party network providers, which creates blind spots and makes systems more vulnerable.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Dependence on third parties also reduces an organization's direct control over its network infrastructure, making it harder to implement advanced monitoring processes.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Networks are subject to attacks from malicious sources.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] Attacks can be from one of two categories: *passive* and *active*.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] A passive attack occurs when a malicious actor intercepts data traveling across a network, usually without generating any kind of alerts.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] It can be difficult or impossible to know if this kind of attack has occurred.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] For example, a wardriving attack can wirelessly detect the four-way handshake between an access point and a client, and crack the password offline without the owner of the access point ever knowing.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] An active attack occurs when a malicious actor initiates commands targeting the network or network resources.
[src:aws-waf/network-security] This is generally meant to disrupt the network's normal operation, conduct reconnaissance, or attempt lateral movements to find and gain access to assets available via the network.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:aws-waf/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:aws-waf/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
